<h3>Analysis of the Southwest Freeway Congestion Mitigation Study</h3>

<div class="textblock"> <span class="italic" style="padding-right: 30px;">Page created November 8, 2015, last updated November 14, 2015</span> </div>

<div class="textblock">Comments and feedback to <a href="mailto:houston@oscarmail.net">Houston@oscarmail.net</a></div>

<div class="textblock">Official project web site: <a href="http://www.mysouthwestfreeway.com/">MySouthwestFreeway.com</a></div>



@*<div class="textblock">
    TxDOT’s recommendation for downtown freeways and Interstate 45 North is the most influential recommendation for Houston’s freeways since the 1950s. 
TxDOT and its partners deserve credit for a bold plan to fully modernize downtown Houston freeways and enhance mobility.
However, review of the preliminary schematics reveals numerous points of concern which could compromise the ability of the new freeway system to meet current and future needs.
</div>*@
@*<div style="color:red; font-weight: bold; padding-bottom: 10px;">UPDATE SEPT 28, 2015: TxDOT has recently posted updated schematics on the project web site. This analysis will be updated in early October.</div>*@

@*<div class="bold">Updates resulting from July 22 and September 4, 2015, meetings with TxDOT</div>*@


<div class="textItem">This objective of  the <a href="http://www.mysouthwestfreeway.com/">Southwest Freeway Congestion Mitigation Study</a> is to identify relatively low-cost measures to reduce traffic congestion.</div>

@*<div class="textItem">While these changes should provide some benefit to the main lane traffic flow, they will impose very substantial negative impacts on the frontage roads, traffic entering or leaving the freeway, and potentially the HOV lane.</div>*@

<div class="bold" style="padding-bottom: 4px; padding-top: 4px;">General Observations </div>
    <ul>
        <li>Inside the loop, this plan generally improves main lane traffic flow by moving traffic load onto the frontage roads, causing more congestion on the frontage roads and its intersections</li>
        <li>While these changes may benefit the main lanes during rush hour, at all other times the changes inside the loop will be a big inconvenience to motorists, especially the removal of the San Jacinto on-ramp</li>
        <li>Many motorists entering or exiting the freeway inside the loop will need to go through an additional frontage road intersection, causing inconvenience and delays</li>
        <li>Converting the HOV lane to two-way operation will be difficult and costly in certain areas, and will also probably violate good design standards. There is no need for two-way operation outside the loop, and inside the loop
            a two-way HOV facility can only be justified from Buffalo Speedway eastward to around Mandel.
        </li>    

    </ul>

<div class="textItem">In my opinion, many of the proposed changes are not worth the financial cost and negative impact, and some changes need additional refinement to make them suitable for implementation.</div>

<div class="bold" style="padding-bottom: 4px; padding-top: 4px;">My Qualifications</div>
    <ul>
        <li>I commute daily on the Southwest Freeway from Beechnut to Loop 610</li>
        <li>In 2012 and 2013 I commuted daily from Beechnut to downtown</li>
    </ul>


