<a name="southbound"></a>
<div class="problem-heading">There is a potential for huge problems on the southbound frontage road between Buffalo Speedway and Weslayan</div>

<div class="textblock">
    <div>
        This section of frontage road already gets jammed, and getting on the on-ramp can be difficult if you are making a right from Timmons. 
    </div>
    <div class="problem-solution">Problem</div>
    <ul>
        <li>Traffic coming from Kirby will be directed to this section of frontage road, adding a lot of traffic</li>
        <li>More traffic will be added by the closure of the Newcastle off-ramp, since those vehicles will need to exit at Weslayan.</li>
        <li>There will be more lane-switching, since the traffic originating from Kirby will need to get into the left lane for the freeway on-ramp, and traffic coming from Buffalo Speedway will need to cross over the Kirby traffic and traffic exiting the freeway,
            and the exit ramp will have more traffic due to the closure of the Newcastle exit
        </li>
        <li>The on-ramp will likely be seriously overloaded and could back a long distance, much longer than the current backups. In fact, it could become gridlock.</li>

    </ul>
    <div class="problem-solution">Potential Solution</div>
    <ul>
        <li>Do not close the Newcastle exit</li>
        <li>Add a lane to the frontage road</li>
        <li>Possibly make the on-ramp east of Weslayan two lanes to avoid huge backups on the frontage road. The two lanes would need to be merged to one lane before the on-ramp west of Weslayan</li>
    </ul>
    <a href="#top">Back to top</a>
</div>

<div>
    <img src="@Url.Content("~/images/us59-plan-analysis/outbound-access-management-annotated.jpg")" />
    <a href="#top">Back to top</a>
</div>

<a name="newcastle"></a>
<div class="problem-heading">The negative impact of the removing the Newcastle exit will probably exceed the benefit</div>
<div class="textblock">
    <div>
        Generally speaking, exit ramps are good for main lane traffic flow since they remove traffic. However, for the Newcastle ramp some lane-switching is needed to reach the ramp, and this plan seeks to eliminate the lane switching.
        </div>
    <div>
        But since this exit has a low-to-moderate volume, I don't recall a big lane switching issue caused by this exit when I commuted through this area. The much bigger problem is the lane-switching for main lane vehicles going to the Loop 610 exit, and vehicles entering from
        the Weslayan on-ramp moving to the left to get in the US 59 main lanes.
    </div>
    <div class="problem-solution">Problem</div>
    <ul>
        <li>Removal of the Newcastle exit will force traffic to exit at Weslayan, contributing to traffic on that section of frontage road and at the Weslayan intersection.</li>
        <li>The Newcastle exit also serves vehicles going to Richmond</li>
        <li>The potenital benefit of this change is for the main lanes during afternoon rush hour only; at all other times the loss of this exit will be an inconvenience</li>

    </ul>
    <div class="problem-solution">Potential Solution</div>
    <ul>
        <li>Do not remove the exit.</li>
    </ul>
    <a href="#top">Back to top</a>
</div>




<a name="northbound"></a>
<div class="problem-heading">Northbound Frontage Road at Buffalo Speedway <span style="color: red;">FIXED: This issue has been fixed by a design revision</span></div>
<div class="textblock">
    <div>The original plan showed the removal of the inbound exit ramp to Kirby, which would have forced traffic going to Kirby to exit for Buffalo Speedway and pass through the Buffalo Speedway intersection.</div>

    <div>The new plan posted on the web site around the date of the public meeting (12-November-2015) shows the exit to Kirby remaining, so this potential cocern no longer exists.</div>

    <div>The main effect of the revised plan (which also existed in the original plan) is that vehicles entering the freeway going northbound from Kirby will have to pass through the Shepherd and Greenbriar intersections since the on-ramp east of Kirby will be removed.
        I think the requirement to go through the Shepherd and Greenbriar intersections will be tolerable.
    </div>

    <a href="#top">Back to top</a>
</div>


<a name="fountainview"></a>
<div class="problem-heading">Converting the exterior shoulder to a traffic lane at at Fountainview will violate safety standards</div>
<div class="textblock">

    <div class="problem-solution">Problem</div>
    <ul>
        <li>There will be seven traffic lanes with no outside shoulder. If the HOV lane is converted to two-way operation, there will be eight lanes</li>
        <li>I drive this section daily and I don't think the traffic going to the Westpark tollway exit is causing slowdowns. Normally this area moves decently, and then traffic slows or stops on the Westpark overpass</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="problem-solution">Potential Solution</div>
    <ul>
        <li>Widen the freeway so there will be an outside shoulder with the new lane</li>
        <li>OR, do not convert the shoulder to a traffic lane
        </li>
    </ul>

</div>

<div>
