<a name="atm"></a>
<div class="problem-heading">While the traffic system management is reported to have a huge benefit-to-cost ratio of 7.6, it is still quite expensive and will add a very large number of overhead signs</div>
<div class="textblock">

    <div class="problem-solution">Observation</div>
    <ul>
        <li>The active traffic management is reported to have a cost of <b>$72 million</b> and a benefit of $550 million. That is still a major cost, and I'm somewhat skeptical the benefits will be that large.</li>
        <li>There will be a huge number of overhead signs and roadside signs: 32 sign bridges with lane assignment DMS (nearly 3 per mile), 5 full-color matrix DMS, and 36 detour DMS along alternative routes and arterials</li>
        <li>The existing changeable message sign near Westpark is useful. Instead of a massive array of signs, I'm thinking a few more signs like the existing sign will be helpful, with the possible addition of signs along arterials which feed into the freeway.</li>

    </ul>
    <div class="problem-solution">Questions</div>
    <ul>
        <li>Is it really necessary to have so many signs to achieve the benefit of active traffic management?</li>
        <li>Could we achieve most of ths benefit while spending a lot less money?</li>
    </ul>
    <a href="#top">Back to top</a>
</div>


<a name="relocate"></a>
<div class="problem-heading">Consider moving the HOV lane to be along Westpark Road on the Metro right-of-way</div>
<div class="textblock">
    <div>
        Maybe the option of moving the HOV lane(s) to the Metro Westpark right-of-way has been considered. But if it has not been considered, it should be looked at. 
    </div>
    <div>
        The HOV lane modifications are projected to cost <b>$240 million</b>.
        If that much money is going to be spent, it should be enough to remove that HOV lane(s) from the main freeway and move it to the nearby right-of-way owned by Metro. This would have a lot of advantages, as summarized below.
    </div>

    <div class="problem-solution">Relocate HOV lanes</div>
    <ul>
        <li>From the Westpark curve to east of Shepherd, move the HOV lane off the freeway and build a new facility on the Metro right-of-way</li>
        <li>Where Metro still wants to use the corridor for rail (around Edloe to Loop 610), the facility would need to be designed to accommodate light rail, most likely by being elevated.</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="problem-solution">Advantages</div>
    <ul>
        <li>The existing HOV lane (about 22 feet wide including barrier) would become available for auxiliary and/or additional freeway lanes
        </li>
        <li>This will greatly simplify making a two-way HOV in the areas around Loop 610 and Edloe. (However, as noted above, I don't think there should be a two-way HOV except from Buffalo Speedway to Mandell)
        </li>
        <li>There is also the possibility of a non-reversible inbound HOV from Buffalo Speedway to Mandell, and then a reversible HOV on the Westpark Corridor to duplicate the existing HOV lane.
        </li>
        <li>Metro could potentially receive compensation or a credit for making the right-of-way available, earning them money or relieving them of any financial obligation for this project.
        </li>

    </ul>
</div>

